bird brains.

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:56.180
One of the most famous examples of crow intelligence
is the way they make hooks to get food.

00:00:56.180 --> 00:01:00.530
One study published in the journal Philosophical
Transactions B found that crows on New Caledonia,

00:01:00.530 --> 00:01:05.340
a South Pacific island, take stripes of leaves
and shape them into hooks to get food out

00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:08.090
of tricky places, like grubs out of tree stumps.

00:01:08.090 --> 00:01:12.650
Another study in PLOS One found that they
understand complex concepts like water displacement.

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:16.160
Like in Aesops fables when a bird drops a
pebble in a glass to raise the water level

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:18.800
so he can drink it, they can actually do that.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:21.470
There’s all sorts of stories of crows getting
clever for food.

00:01:21.470 --> 00:01:25.920
In Japan, crows will place walnuts in the
middle of the road, then fly away and wait

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:27.830
for a car to drive over them, cracking it
open.

00:01:27.830 --> 00:01:31.220
If it doesn’t work the first time, the crow
will move the walnut to another place in the

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:32.500
road and try again.

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:36.630
I mean most human kids don’t know how to
