00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:57.950
Yeah I’m not kidding on that one.

00:01:57.950 --> 00:02:00.830
How do they do this if they have such tiny
and different brains.

00:02:00.830 --> 00:02:04.860
Well one study published in the journal Nature
Communications describes how.

00:02:04.860 --> 00:02:08.200
Most of our big brained smarts lies in the
prefrontal cortex.

00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:12.100
Scientists think this area is responsible
for things like reason and controlling emotions.

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:14.150
But birds don’t have this.

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:17.300
Their smarts evolved convergently, or independently
from ours.

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:23.750
Instead, the seat of crow’s intelligence
lies in the nidopallium caudolaterale.

00:02:23.750 --> 00:02:27.780
This part of the brain helps the crow form
memories, learn and even make predictions.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:31.370
Why did they evolve such complicated brains?

00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:33.770
Researchers think their environment plays
a big role.

00:02:33.770 --> 00:02:38.140
The crow family can be found in variety of
ecosystems and eat a variety of food, so they’d

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:40.730
have to be able to adapt to changing landscapes.

00:02:40.730 --> 00:02:43.300
Like humans, they are very social creatures.

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:47.099
And solving both social and ecological problems
required bigger brains.

